<font color="#FF0000">BEYOND VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec 26 23:35:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I wonder how we define those who fought for freedom.<br>
Certainly we define it as meaning those soldiers who<br>
went to war. <br><br>
I fought for freedom. I was an active anti-war protester<br>
who gave years of my life to focus on ending a war that<br>
was trying to limit the freedom of the Vietnamese people<br>
to determine their own fate. I see the war as one in<br>
which the US was an outside force trying to control<br>
the destiny of a nation for reasons that had nothing<br>
to do with the will or desires of the Vietnamese people.<br>
I fought for freedom. <br><br>
I believe that US soldiers also believe that they fought<br>
for freedom. While I disagree with the reality, I do <br>
believe that many soldiers did what they thought was right<br>
and just, given the news stories and the US gov't<br>
dis-information. To these soldiers I have only respect<br>
and honor. To those who knew the truth and did led the<br>
war effort (e.g. McNamara and his ilk) I see them as<br>
criminals for their actions.<br><br>
As for the MIA's, their spirits are with us regardless<br>
of the location of their bodies. To me this is the<br>
most important fact for us to keep in mind. Honor those<br>
who have died, and the walking wounded with peace<br>
and justice for Vietnam .
<p><code>-- jproujan@k12s.phast.umass.edu  (Jed Proujansky) </code><p>


